# 🚀 Complete Setup & Deployment Guide

## Quick Start

This guide will walk you through setting up and deploying the Twitch Emote Tracker to Vercel.

---

## Step 1: Local Setup

### 1.1 Install Node.js
- Download from [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org/) (version 14 or higher)
- Verify installation: `node --version` and `npm --version`

### 1.2 Create Project Directory
```bash
mkdir twitch-emote-tracker
cd twitch-emote-tracker
```

### 1.3 Copy Files
Copy all the provided files into your project directory:
```
twitch-emote-tracker/
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/
│       └── deploy.yml
├── public/
│   └── index.html
├── src/
│   ├── components/
│   │   ├── ChatPanel.jsx
│   │   ├── ControlsPanel.jsx
│   │   ├── PromotionModal.jsx
│   │   └── StatsPanel.jsx
│   ├── app.jsx
│   ├── index.jsx
│   ├── index.css
├── .gitignore
├── package.json
├── postcss.config.js
├── README.md
├── tailwind.config.js
└── vercel.json
```

### 1.4 Install Dependencies
```bash
npm install
```

This will install:
- React 18.2.0
- React DOM
- React Scripts
- Lucide React icons
- Tailwind CSS (via PostCSS)

### 1.5 Run Locally
```bash
npm start
```

The app will open at `http://localhost:3000`. You can now test the tracker locally!

---

## Step 2: Prepare for GitHub

### 2.1 Create GitHub Repository

1. Go to [github.com](https://github.com) and sign in
2. Click "+" → "New repository"
3. Name it `twitch-emote-tracker`
4. Choose "Public" (recommended for easier setup)
5. Click "Create repository"

### 2.2 Initialize Git Locally

From your project directory:

```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: Twitch emote tracker"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/twitch-emote-tracker.git
git push -u origin main
```

Replace `YOUR_USERNAME` with your actual GitHub username.

### 2.3 Verify on GitHub

Go to your repository on GitHub and confirm all files are there.

---

## Step 3: Deploy to Vercel

### Option A: Via GitHub (Recommended - Automatic)

#### 3A.1 Connect Vercel to GitHub
1. Go to [vercel.com](https://vercel.com)
2. Sign up or log in (you can use your GitHub account)
3. Click "New Project"
4. Click "Continue with GitHub" (or link your GitHub if prompted)
5. Find your `twitch-emote-tracker` repository
6. Click "Import"

#### 3A.2 Configure Project
- **Project Name**: `twitch-emote-tracker` (or your preferred name)
- **Framework**: React
- **Build Command**: `npm run build` (should auto-detect)
- **Output Directory**: `build` (should auto-detect)
- **Environment Variables**: None needed (leave blank)

#### 3A.3 Deploy
Click "Deploy" and wait 1-2 minutes for it to complete.

**Your site is now live!** Vercel will give you a `.vercel.app` URL.

#### 3A.4 Custom Domain (Optional)
To use your own domain or a custom subdomain:
1. Go to your project settings on Vercel
2. Click "Domains"
3. Add your domain and follow DNS setup instructions

---

### Option B: Via Vercel CLI (Manual Deploy)

#### 3B.1 Install Vercel CLI
```bash
npm install -g vercel
```

#### 3B.2 Login to Vercel
```bash
vercel login
```

This opens a browser to authenticate.

#### 3B.3 Deploy
```bash
vercel
```

Follow the prompts:
- **Set up and deploy?** → Yes
- **Which scope?** → Your personal account
- **Project name?** → `twitch-emote-tracker`
- **In which directory?** → `.` (current)
- **Want to override existing settings?** → No

Your site deploys immediately!

---

## Step 4: Set Up Auto-Deployment

Once connected to GitHub via Vercel, every time you push code to your `main` branch, Vercel automatically rebuilds and deploys.

### Make Changes & Auto-Deploy

```bash
# Make changes to files
# Then commit and push:

git add .
git commit -m "Update feature description"
git push
```

Your site updates automatically within 1-2 minutes!

---

## Step 5: Customize Your Tracker

### Change the Bot Promo Modal
Edit `/src/components/PromotionModal.jsx`:
- Change the title and description
- Modify the feature list
- Update links and buttons

### Change Tracked Emotes
Edit `/src/app.jsx`, find the `detectEmotes()` function:
```javascript
const detectEmotes = (message) => {
  const words = message.split(/\s+/);
  let hasWW = false;
  let hasLL = false;

  words.forEach((word) => {
    const cleanWord = word.replace(/[^a-zA-Z0-9]/g, '');
    if (emoteMap[cleanWord]) {
      // Change these conditions to track different emotes:
      if (cleanWord.toLowerCase().includes('ww')) {
        hasWW = true;
      }
      if (cleanWord.toLowerCase().includes('ll')) {
        hasLL = true;
      }
    }
  });

  return { hasWW, hasLL };
};
```

### Change Colors
Edit `/tailwind.config.js`:
```javascript
theme: {
  extend: {
    colors: {
      // Add custom colors here
    },
  },
},
```

Or directly modify Tailwind class names in components (e.g., `text-cyan-400` → `text-pink-400`).

---

## Troubleshooting

### Build Fails with "npm not found"
- Ensure Node.js is installed: `node --version`
- Try: `npm install` then `npm run build`

### Vercel Deploy Shows Blank Page
1. Check build logs on Vercel dashboard
2. Ensure all files are committed to GitHub: `git status`
3. Verify `public/index.html` exists
4. Check browser console for errors (F12)

### Chat Not Connecting
1. Open browser console (F12)
2. Check for errors from Twitch API
3. Verify channel name spelling (case-insensitive)
4. Check that TMI.js script loaded properly

### Emotes Not Detecting
1. Verify 7TV emotes exist for the channel
2. Check browser console for 7TV API errors
3. Try a different channel to test
4. Emotes might not have "ww" or "ll" in their names

### Want to Update Code Later?
```bash
# Make changes to your code files
git add .
git commit -m "Describe your changes"
git push origin main

# Vercel automatically redeploys!
# Check your deployment at vercel.com/dashboard
```

